Data Science Final Project-Global Military Expenditure For the Last Decade¶

Yanru Heng¶

https://github.com/hengyr/FinalProject.git

Abstract¶

By looking into the coutries' expenditure from 2009-2018, the study found there's a correlation with GDP, region and income group of each country. Also the study cluster the numbers as a type of ranking showing USA and China both hold a specific tier while a few coutries like UK, France, India forms a third tier.

Introduction and Background¶

Living in a time of globalization and information, military activities are becoming a less common but necessary elements for each country. By looking at these data we could analyze the "superpower" situation of the world. The dataset is from the world bank and also GDP data from world bank is also added in later questions. Generally we are trying to answer three major question:

  1. By merging the GDP data of world bank dataset, what's the relationship between GDP situation related to the military expense? Is there necessarily a correlation? In another words, does a high GDP definitely reflect on a high military expense?
  2. How should we classify the world miltary expense by clustering the expense situations of the last decade?
  3. Considering percentage of GDP would go to military expenses for each country,are they generally even? Does different regions and income groups vary? Is there a correlation with GDP?

Methods¶

The data contains military expense from 1960 to 2018. I only included the 2009-2018 data which is the last decade. As this should be a very professional and comprehensive data, missing values in this range would not be common for most major countries, I just excluded all the countries with missing values if in any column. 137 countries remained after cleaning which is still considerably sufficient and large enough to justify and world's situation.

A lot of python libraries were called to apply including Ipython.display, pandas,numpy, matplotlib.pyplot, matplotlib, seaborn, statistics, sklearn.preprocessing, sklearn.decomposition, and sklearn.cluster.

I used the merge function to add in the GDP data. I used boxplot and bar plot to present the general situation in many cases. Also scatterplots sometimes with best fit line to see if there's correlations to answer some of the questions. For clustering, I used scaling and principal component analysis and to form K-means clustering. But the most effective clustering comes from hierarchical clustering. For question 1 and many EDAs, I mostly use the mean and some medians of expenses to evaluate. And for question 3, I used the means of expenses and GDP to find the ratio.

The plots show the median and mean of ratio of GDP contributes to GDP according to regions and income groups. Unlike the EDA showing the military expenditure grouped by regions and income groups in appendix, north america is not taking the lead. Middle East and North Africa is taking a significant lead which makes sense considering the state of peace in that area are usually at risk. Besides that, North America is still leading but not with much differences between region. If we look at the income groups, low income groups are less likely to use their GDP into military expenditure. While if we considerign the mean, low-middle income group is also considerably low.

Generally I would say no matter the GDP is, the ratio is almost similar. although the fit line shows the slightly positive cases due to USA, The shadowing is very symmertric. At low ends of GDP, the ratio even varies largely. I would say region and income group are much influential varibales.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, the military expenditure, as least for the past decade, is correlated with GDP. It is also influence by the regions and income group the country is in while north america countries tend to spend a lot and low come and lower middle income countries spend less. Countries in the middle-east tend to spent a lot considering their GDP in the military while low income groups are much less. USA is leading the military expenditure in every category and the leading gap is enormous. China's second place forms its own tier as well and had a big lead as well. Gernmany, France, UK, India, Japan, Russia, Saudi Arabia made up a considerable expenditure as a tier. And those are the cases that bring up the news most commonly.

data = data.set_index([exp['Name']])

data_scaled=scaler.transform(data)

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

pca_scores=pca.fit_transform(data_scaled)
